					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/fuzzyboots" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1229418); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1229418&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610226058" alt="FuzzyBoots" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1229418)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/fuzzyboots" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1229418); return false;" >FuzzyBoots</a></span> <span class="odate time_1323353504 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">08 Dec 2011 14:11</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1324215">
									

<p>Hmm&#8230; well, that's pretty close to a Universal Receiver (AB+ is slightly better IIRC as Rh-negative people cannot receive Rh-positive blood). Also makes it pretty useless for transfusions since only people with blood type AB can receive the red blood cells (although anyone can receive the plasma). It's also a very rare type, less than 1% for all countries. My bet would be that the rarity is why the author included it.</p>
<p>And yes, the ABO and Rh systems are just two systems for blood matching, but they're close enough for 99% of the cases.</p>

							</div>

								
					
